rban Art Gallery]] and cemeteries to only allow 50 people at a time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/lifestyle/383319/durban-bans-swimming-at-the-beach/|title=Durban bans swimming at the beach|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n*[[Fake news]] spread to the effect that [[5G|5G cellular]] technology was the true cause of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] symptoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/lifestyle/technology/2263396/zweli-mkhize-says-5g-causing-covid-19-deaths-is-just-fake-news/|title=Zweli Mkhize says \u20185G causing Covid-19 deaths\u2019 is just fake news|last=Cilliers|first=Charles|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Economic impact===\nAt the beginning of the national shutdown on the 27 March South African economists predicted that the pandemic could cause a 2.5% to 10% contraction of [[Economy of South Africa|South Africa's total GDP]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/economy/sa-economy-could-crater-up-to-10-this-year/|title=SA economy could crater up to 10% this year|date=2020-03-25|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The national lockdown and resulting economic slowdown reduced demand for electricity by more than 7 500 MW thereby temporarily reducing the impact of the long running [[South African energy crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/eskom-will-keep-the-lights-on-during-21-day-lockdown-45708578\n|title=Eskom will keep the lights on during 21-day lockdown\n|date=2020-03-28\n|publisher=Independent Media\n|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n====Stock market news====\nThe [[JSE Limited|JSE]] lost 15% of its value in the week ending 13 March 2020, its worst week in 21 years.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/markets/2020-03-13-market-wrap-jse-has-worst-week-since-1998-as-pandemic-plagues-investors/\n|title=MARKET WRAP: JSE has worst week since 1998 as pandemic plagues investors\n|date=2020-03-13\n|first1=Odwa\n|last1=Mjo\n|work=BusinessLIVE\n|accessdate=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[South African Reserve Bank]] governor, [[Lesetja Kganyago]] announced a reduction of the country's [[Repurchase agreement|repo rate]] by 100 basis points or 1 percentage point to 5.25%.<ref name=\"RepoSlashed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/south-africa/live-repo-rate-decision/|title=Repo rate slashed by 1%|last=Mar 2020|first=Suren Naidoo / 19|date=2020-03-19|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n====Banking and retail====\nRetailers like Clicks, [[Pick n Pay Stores|Pick n Pay]], and [[Woolworths Holdings Limited|Woolworths]] have some limitations on the number of the same items customers may buy.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/cornonavirus-linked-panic-buying-retailers-ration-stock-2020-3\n|title=Woolworths stops food demonstrations, limits items per customer - here's what other retailers are doing\n|date=2020-03-19\n|first1=Jay\n|last1=Caboz\n|publisher=Business Insider\n|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 19 March, [[Minister of Trade and Industry (South Africa)|Minister of Trade and Industry]] [[Ebrahim Patel]] signed a government gazette that enforces [[price controls]] on essential items and that could see [[Price gouging|price gougers]] punished with measures including a R10 million fine, a fine equivalent to 10% of a firm's turnover, or [[Imprisonment|12 months in prison]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/business/383217/new-regulations-bring-coronavirus-price-controls-for-certain-high-demand-products-heres-what-is-on-the-list/|title=New regulations bring coronavirus price controls for certain high-demand products \u2013 here's what is on the list|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Standard Bank]] announced a 90-day [[Forbearance|payment holiday]] for small and medium-sized business and students to try and shield them from the economic impact of the outbreak, starting from 1 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/coronavirus-standard-bank-gives-businesses-a-debt-holiday-2020-3|title=Coronavirus: Standard Bank gives businesses, students a debt holiday|website=BusinessInsider|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.gov.za/taxonomy/term/707 South African government statements]\n*[http://www.nicd.ac.za/media/ NICD media]\n*[https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) outbreak]\n*[https://sacoronavirus.co.za/ Official government website for information about Coronavirus in South Africa]\n*[https://t.me/CoronaZABot Corona Telegram Bot for South Africa]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jeandr\u00e9 du Toit", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:can't sentence properly", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Africa"}
{"title_page": "Lubunca", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|for=grammar|date=March 2020}}\n{{Expand Turkish|Lubunca|date=March 2020}}\n'''Lubunca''', '''Labunca''' or '''Lubunyaca''' is a secret Turkish queer [[LGBT slang|slang]] and [[argot]] used by [[LGBT]]Q community in [[LGBT history in Turkey|Turkey]].<ref name=\"if2\">{{cite web|url=http://2010.ifistanbul.com/en/Program/Event?typeid=3|title=Nakka!|accessdate=27 January 2012|last=|first=|quote=|date=11 February 2010|publisher=If \u0130stanbul|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"bianet2\">{{cite web|url=http://bianet.org/bianet/toplum/119989-sanatcilardan-ayrimciliga-nakka|title=Sanat\u00e7\u0131lardan Ayr\u0131mc\u0131l\u0131\u011fa \"Nakka!\"|accessdate=25 January 2012|last=|first=|quote=|date=11 February 2010|publisher=Bianet.org|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224195155/http://bianet.org/bianet/toplum/119989-sanatcilardan-ayrimciliga-nakka|archivedate=24 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The term originated from the root ''lubni'', that is the Romani word for \"prostitute\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Lubunya : transseks\u00fcel kimlik ve beden|last=Berghan, Selin.|date=2007|publisher=Metis Yay\u0131nlar\u0131|isbn=978-9753425698|location=\u0130stanbul|pages=1|oclc=870275467}}</ref> Even though originally attributed to this group, Lubunca is currently used more widely within the LGBTQ community.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Islamic homosexualities : culture, history, and literature|last=Murray, Stephen O.|others=Roscoe, Will|isbn=0814774679|location=New York|oclc=35526232|date = February 1997}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nLubunca is derived from slang used by [[Romani language|Romani people]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=James Baldwin's Turkish decade : erotics of exile|last=Zaborowska, Magdalena J.|date=2009|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=9780822341444|location=Durham|pages=150|oclc=209335625}}</ref><ref name=\"Romanca2\">{{cite web|url=http://bianet.org/biamag/toplumsal-cinsiyet/108442-stonewall-dan-lambda-ya-onur-yuruyusu|title=Stonewall'dan Lambda'ya Onur Y\u00fcr\u00fcy\u00fc\u015f\u00fc|accessdate=25 January 2012|last=\u00d6rer|first=Ay\u00e7a|date=19 July 2008|publisher=Bianet.org|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414165419/http://bianet.org/biamag/toplumsal-cinsiyet/108442-stonewall-dan-lambda-ya-onur-yuruyusu|archivedate=14 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>. It contains terms from other languages, including [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Arabic]], [[Armenian language|Armenian]] and [[French language|French]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arsiv.sabah.com.tr/2006/11/03/gun97.html|title=SABAH - 03/11/2006 - \u0130stanbul'daki gay d\u00fcnyas\u0131|website=arsiv.sabah.com.tr|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://next.liberation.fr/culture/2006/11/03/tour-de-gay-a-istanbul_56274|title=Tour de gay \u00e0 Istanbul|date=2006-11-03|website=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|language=fr|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\nLubunca is an argot of approximately four hundred words<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/1999/07/17/yasam/kay.html|title=Kay\u0131p gecelerin gizli dili!|language=tr|website=Radikal|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref> and was spoken by the [[K\u00f6\u00e7ek|k\u00f6\u00e7eks]] and ''[http://www.qrd.org/qrd/www/world/europe/turkey/islamottoman.htm tellaks]'' between the 17th and 18th centuries<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gzone.com.tr/ozel-dosya-lubuncanin-osmanliya-dayanan-tarihcesi-ve-lubunca-sozluk/|title=\u00d6ZEL DOSYA: E\u015eC\u0130NSEL ARGOSU LUBUNCA|date=2015-02-25|website=GZONE|language=tr|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>. It was later adopted and developed by [[Transvestism|transvestites]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arsiv.sabah.com.tr/2006/11/03/gun97.html|title=\u0130stanbul'daki gay d\u00fcnyas\u0131|last=|first=|date=|website=arsiv.sabah.com.tr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref> It is believed that it was developed to avoid persecution while secretly communicating in public areas.  It has been in use since the late Ottoman era .<ref name=\"Ay\u00e7a \u00d6rer2\">{{cite web|url=http://bianet.org/bianet/kultur/97318-cirkin-ordek-yavrularinin-gercek-masali|title=\u00c7irkin \u00d6rdek Yavrular\u0131n\u0131n Ger\u00e7ek Masal\u0131|accessdate=25 January 2012|last=\u00d6rer|first=Ay\u00e7a|date=9 June 2007|publisher=Bianet.org|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402152500/http://bianet.org/bianet/kultur/97318-cirkin-ordek-yavrularinin-gercek-masali|archivedate=2 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Terminology ==\nIn Lubunca, ''manti'' means pleasant or beautiful. ''Balamoz'' describes old males.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeoutistanbul.com/gaylezbiyen/makale/101/Lubunca-s%C3%B6zl%C3%BCk/|title=Lubunca s\u00f6zl\u00fck|accessdate=24 January 2012|last=|first=|date=2007|publisher=Time Out dergisi|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429012306/http://www.timeoutistanbul.com/gaylezbiyen/makale/101/Lubunca-s%C3%B6zl%C3%BCk|archivedate=29 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Madilik'' means evil<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kaosgl.com/sayfa.php?id=5083|title=Akl\u0131m\u0131 Ba\u015f\u0131mdan Al Benim|accessdate=24 January 2012|last=Yaman|first=Can|date=1 July 2010|publisher=[[Kaos GL]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910141149/http://www.kaosgl.com/sayfa.php?id=5083|archivedate=10 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and ''gull\u00fcm'' means fun.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bianet.org/bianet/toplumsal-cinsiyet/130615-lak-parti-durmak-yok-gullume-devam|title=Lak Parti: \"Durmak Yok, Gull\u00fcme Devam\"|accessdate=25 January 2012|last=|first=|date=9 June 2011|publisher=Bianet.org|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809010458/http://www.bianet.org/bianet/toplumsal-cinsiyet/130615-lak-parti-durmak-yok-gullume-devam|archivedate=9 August 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>T\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|LGBT|Turkey}}\n* [[LGBT slang]]\n* [[Polari]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* \"[http://www.timeoutistanbul.com/gaylezbiyen/makale/101/Lubunca-s%C3%B6zl%C3%BCk/ Lubunca s\u00f6zl\u00fck]\" at TimeOut \u0130stanbul\n\n[[Category:LGBT linguistics]]\n[[Category:LGBT culture in Turkey]]\n[[Category:LGBT slang]]\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|for=grammar|date=March 2020}}\n{{Expand Turkish|Lubunca|date=March 2020}}\n'''Lubunca''', '''Labunca''' or '''Lubunyaca''' is a [[LGBT slang|slang]] and [[argot]] used by [[LGBT]] individuals in [[LGBT history in Turkey|Turkey]].<ref name=\"if2\">{{cite web|url=http://2010.ifistanbul.com/en/Program/Event?typeid=3|title=Nakka!|accessdate=27 January 2012|last=|first=|quote=|date=11 February 2010|publisher=If \u0130stanbul|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"bianet2\">{{cite web|url=http://bianet.org/bianet/toplum/119989-sanatcilardan-ayrimciliga-nakka|title=Sanat\u00e7\u0131lardan Ayr\u0131mc\u0131l\u0131\u011fa \"Nakka!\"|accessdate=25 January 2012|last=|first=|quote=|date=11 February 2010|publisher=Bianet.org|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224195155/http://bianet.org/bianet/toplum/119989-sanatcilardan-ayrimciliga-nakka|archivedate=24 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The term originated from the word ''lubunya'', which refers to homosexual feminine or transsexual people.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Lubunya : transseks\u00fcel kimlik ve beden|last=Berghan, Selin.|date=2007|publisher=Metis Yay\u0131nlar\u0131|isbn=978-9753425698|location=\u0130stanbul|pages=1|oclc=870275467}}</ref> Even though originally attributed to this group, it is currently used more widely within the LGBT community.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Islamic homosexualities : culture, history, and literature|last=Murray, Stephen O.|others=Roscoe, Will|isbn=0814774679|location=New York|oclc=35526232|date = February 1997}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nLubunca is derived from slang used by [[Romani language|Romani people]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=James Baldwin's Turkish decade : erotics of exile|last=Zaborowska, Magdalena J.|date=2009|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=9780822341444|location=Durham|pages=150|oclc=209335625}}</ref><ref name=\"Romanca2\">{{cite web|url=http://bianet.org/biamag/toplumsal-cinsiyet/108442-stonewall-dan-lambda-ya-onur-yuruyusu|title=Stonewall'dan Lambda'ya Onur Y\u00fcr\u00fcy\u00fc\u015f\u00fc|accessdate=25 January 2012|last=\u00d6rer|first=Ay\u00e7a|date=19 July 2008|publisher=Bianet.org|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414165419/http://bianet.org/biamag/toplumsal-cinsiyet/108442-stonewall-dan-lambda-ya-onur-yuruyusu|archivedate=14 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>. It contains terms from other languages, including [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Arabic]], [[Armenian language|Armenian]] and [[French language|French]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arsiv.sabah.com.tr/2006/11/03/gun97.html|title=SABAH - 03/11/2006 - \u0130stanbul'daki gay d\u00fcnyas\u0131|website=arsiv.sabah.com.tr|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://next.liberation.fr/culture/2006/11/03/tour-de-gay-a-istanbul_56274|title=Tour de gay \u00e0 Istanbul|date=2006-11-03|website=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|language=fr|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\nLubunca is an argot of approximately four hundred words<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/1999/07/17/yasam/kay.html|title=Kay\u0131p gecelerin gizli dili!|language=tr|website=Radikal|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref> and was spoken by the [[K\u00f6\u00e7ek|k\u00f6\u00e7eks]] and ''[http://www.qrd.org/qrd/www/world/europe/turkey/islamottoman.htm tellaks]'' between the 17th and 18th centuries<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gzone.com.tr/ozel-dosya-lubuncanin-osmanliya-dayanan-tarihcesi-ve-lubunca-sozluk/|title=\u00d6ZEL DOSYA: E\u015eC\u0130NSEL ARGOSU LUBUNCA|date=2015-02-25|website=GZONE|language=tr|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>. It was later adopted and developed by [[Transvestism|transvestites]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arsiv.sabah.com.tr/2006/11/03/gun97.html|title=\u0130stanbul'daki gay d\u00fcnyas\u0131|last=|first=|date=|website=arsiv.sabah.com.tr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref> It is believed that it was developed to avoid persecution while secretly communicating in public areas.  It has been in use since the late Ottoman era .<ref name=\"Ay\u00e7a \u00d6rer2\">{{cite web|url=http://bianet.org/bianet/kultur/97318-cirkin-ordek-yavrularinin-gercek-masali|title=\u00c7irkin \u00d6rdek Yavrular\u0131n\u0131n Ger\u00e7ek Masal\u0131|accessdate=25 January 2012|last=\u00d6rer|first=Ay\u00e7a|date=9 June 2007|publisher=Bianet.org|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402152500/http://bianet.org/bianet/kultur/97318-cirkin-ordek-yavrularinin-gercek-masali|archivedate=2 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Terminology ==\nIn Lubunca, ''manti'' means pleasant or beautiful. ''Balamoz'' describes old males.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeoutistanbul.com/gaylezbiyen/makale/101/Lubunca-s%C3%B6zl%C3%BCk/|title=Lubunca s\u00f6zl\u00fck|accessdate=24 January 2012|last=|first=|date=2007|publisher=Time Out dergisi|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429012306/http://www.timeoutistanbul.com/gaylezbiyen/makale/101/Lubunca-s%C3%B6zl%C3%BCk|archivedate=29 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Madilik'' means evil<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kaosgl.com/sayfa.php?id=5083|title=Akl\u0131m\u0131 Ba\u015f\u0131mdan Al Benim|accessdate=24 January 2012|last=Yaman|first=Can|date=1 July 2010|publisher=[[Kaos GL]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910141149/http://www.kaosgl.com/sayfa.php?id=5083|archivedate=10 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and ''gull\u00fcm'' means fun.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bianet.org/bianet/toplumsal-cinsiyet/130615-lak-parti-durmak-yok-gullume-devam|title=Lak Parti: \"Durmak Yok, Gull\u00fcme Devam\"|accessdate=25 January 2012|last=|first=|date=9 June 2011|publisher=Bianet.org|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809010458/http://www.bianet.org/bianet/toplumsal-cinsiyet/130615-lak-parti-durmak-yok-gullume-devam|archivedate=9 August 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>T\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|LGBT|Turkey}}\n* [[LGBT slang]]\n* [[Polari]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* \"[http://www.timeoutistanbul.com/gaylezbiyen/makale/101/Lubunca-s%C3%B6zl%C3%BCk/ Lubunca s\u00f6zl\u00fck]\" at TimeOut \u0130stanbul\n\n[[Category:LGBT linguistics]]\n[[Category:LGBT culture in Turkey]]\n[[Category:LGBT slang]]\n", "name_user": "Yati1710", "label": "safe", "comment": "Language, grammar, root word correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lubunca"}
